page.text: SUBJECT: Georgetown Family Fare Traffic Study – Planning Commission Submittal
Spartan Stores has proposed the construction of a Family Fare supermarket and mixed-use site in the northwest
Avenue intersection in Georgetown Township, Ottawa County, Michigan.
The general location of the site is shown in Figure 1. The proposed Family Fare site will include a 48,267 square-
foot supermarket with 29,100 square feet of attached retail space, a 1,111 square-foot gas station/convenience
store with eight gas pumps, 22,200 square feet of office space, and 18,554 square feet of detached retail space.
The site will be developed in two phases. The first phase will include the proposed supermarket, 18,000 square
feet of attached retail space, and the gas station and is expected to be completed and open in 2011. The second
phase will include an additional 11,100 square feet of attached retail space, 22,200 square feet of office space on
two outlots, and 18,554 square feet of detached retail space on five outlots and is expected to be complete and
Site access will be provided by three proposed full-access driveways. The first driveway will be located on
Baldwin Street, directly across from an existing driveway for Fairhaven Church, approximately 675 feet west of

This traffic study encompasses an operational analysis of existing (2009), base year (2011), opening year (2011 +
supermarket, retail, and gas station site traffic), and future year (2014 + office and retail site traffic) conditions in
the study area and at the proposed site driveways. The purpose of this study is to determine the traffic impact the
proposed development will have on the various intersections in the study area, and determine the mitigation (if
any) required to provide acceptable operations within the proposed site and at study area intersections.

The Highway Capacity Software (HCS+, Version 5.21), based on the 2000 Highway Capacity Manual (HCM),
was used to determine existing peak hour "Levels of Service" of the traffic movements at the various intersections
in the study area. The term Level of Service (LOS) indicates how well (or poorly) traffic operates based on traffic
volumes, lane configurations, and traffic controls. Each level is determined by the average amount of traffic
control delay experienced by motorists. LOS “A” represents little or no delays while LOS “F” represents
operational failure (extensive delays which may include long vehicular queues). LOS “C” or “D” (or better) is
typically considered acceptable during peak hours for communities like Georgetown Township. The Level-of-
Service criteria, as defined by the HCM, are described in Table 1 for signalized and unsignalized intersections.
Existing (2009) peak-hour LOS values are shown in Figure 4 for those movements that must yield the right-of-way.
Examination of Figure 4 reveals that all of the traffic movements at the study area intersections operate at LOS “D” or
better during the morning and afternoon peak hours. The overall Level of Service for the study area signalized
intersections is shown in Table 2. Capacity analysis worksheets for all existing (2009) intersection capacity
analyses are included in Appendix B of this report.

Based on discussions with the Ottawa County Road Commission (OCRC) regarding historical growth along the

Peak-hour capacity analyses for the base year (2011) condition at the study area intersections were performed
using HCS+. The resultant morning and afternoon peak-hour traffic volumes and LOS values are shown in Figure 5.
Examination of Figure 5 reveals that all of the traffic movements at the study area intersections are anticipated to

overall Level of Service for the study area signalized intersections is shown in Table 3. Capacity analysis
worksheets for all base year (2011) intersection capacity analyses are included in Appendix C of this report.

page.text: The amount of peak-hour traffic generated by the first phase of the proposed Family Fare supermarket site was
determined using Trip Generation, a handbook developed by the Institute of Transportation Engineers (ITE) that
contains information on more than 4,800 trip generation studies nationwide for different land uses. According to
the site plan dated May 12, 2009, the first phase of the development includes a 48,267 square-foot supermarket,
18,000 square feet of attached retail space, and a 1,111 square-foot gas station/convenience store with eight gas
pumps. The number of gas station trips was calculated based on the square footage of the convenience store,
instead of the number of pumps, because it results in a more conservative trip generation estimate. The projected
number of peak-hour trips generated by the proposed Family Fare supermarket site is shown in Table 4 on the

An adjustment for pass-by trips was made for the various first phase land uses for opening year (2011) in Table 4.
A pass-by trip is not a new trip to the street adjacent to the development site, but occurs when a patron is attracted
to the site from passing traffic. The pass-by percentages depicted in Table 4 vary depending on the type of land
use and range from 35% to 50% based on ITE recommendations. Pass-by trips reduce the number of new trips
assigned to the area roadways, but do not reduce the number of driveway trips.
No adjustment for internal trips was made to the trip generation of the first phase of the proposed Family Fare
supermarket site because of the limited number of separate trip generators and because the Shopping Center land
use already incorporates the existence of internal trips.

6.0 Future Year (2014) Analysis with Phase 2 Family Fare Supermarket Site Traffic

page.text: In addition to the opening year (2011) analyses, an analysis of future year (2014) conditions was completed to
determine the impact of the full build-out of the proposed Family Fare supermarket site. Future year (2014)
conditions include the opening year (2011) peak-hour volumes, peak-hour volumes generated by the second phase
of the Family Fare supermarket site, and three years of background traffic growth at an annual compounding rate
The amount of peak-hour traffic generated by the second phase of the proposed Family Fare supermarket site was
determined using Trip Generation. According to the site plan dated May 12, 2009, the second phase of the
development includes several outlots without defined land uses. For the purposes of the future year (2014)
analysis, it was assumed that the second phase of the proposed Family Fare supermarket site will include two
restaurants, a bank, two office buildings, two general retail buildings, and additional attached retail space. The
projected number of peak-hour trips generated by the second phase proposed Family Fare supermarket site is
shown in Table 6 on the next page.

An adjustment for internal trips was made to the trip generation of the second phase of the proposed Family Fare
supermarket site. Internal trips are common at sites with multiple land uses and occur when a patron visits two or
more businesses that can be accessed from the same parking area (i.e. there is no need to enter the main roadway
when going from business to business). The estimated number of internal trips, as shown in Table 6, is based on
ITE recommendations and previous studies. Note that internal trips are not calculated for Land Use Code 820
(Shopping Center) since the trip generation studies for this use already incorporate the existence of internal trips.
An adjustment for pass-by trips was also made to the trip generation of the second phase of the proposed Family
Fare supermarket site. The pass-by percentages depicted in Table 6 vary depending on the type of land use and
range from 35% to 50% based on ITE recommendations. Pass-by trips reduce the number of new trips assigned
to the area roadways, but do not reduce the number of driveway trips.
Traffic generated by the second phase of the Family Fare supermarket site was distributed similarly to the
distribution in the opening year (2011) scenario. Under future year (2014) conditions, 10% of the vehicles
Avenue/Larks Street intersection were reassigned to the proposed northern
Avenue. The trip distribution percentages and traffic assignment volumes are shown in Figure
E.1 and Figure E.2, respectively, in Appendix E of this report. The resulting future year (2014) peak-hour traffic
volumes (opening year volumes + traffic generated by phase two of the Family Fare supermarket site) for the
morning and afternoon peak hours are shown in Figure 7.
Peak-hour capacity analyses for the future year (2014) condition at the study area intersections were performed
using HCS+. The resultant peak-hour LOS values for all traffic movements are shown in Figure 7. The analyses
assumed no change in existing traffic controls or lane configurations along Baldwin Street, 36
Avenue, or Rosewood Street. However, northbound and southbound left-turn lanes were assumed at the 28
Avenue/Lark Street intersection as described in section 5.4 of this report.

4) The study area intersections are anticipated to operate at acceptable Levels of Service under future year
